      <section class="topic" data-topic="1" id="t1">
        <div class="topic-head">
          <h2><span class="tagnum">01.</span> PHP OOP Core: Classes, Interfaces, Traits, Abstracts, Static</h2>
          <div class="topic-controls">
            <span class="diff mid">MID</span>
            <button class="star-btn" data-bm="1">☆</button>
            <button class="check-btn" data-ck="1">✓</button>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p><strong>Explanation.</strong> A <strong>class</strong> defines the blueprint (properties + methods); an <strong>interface</strong> defines a contract — method signatures only, no implementation — that any implementing class must fulfill, enabling polymorphism without inheritance. An <strong>abstract class</strong> sits between the two: it can hold real implementation and state like a normal class, but can also declare abstract methods that subclasses <em>must</em> implement, and it can't be instantiated directly. A <strong>trait</strong> is PHP's answer to the lack of multiple inheritance — it lets you literally paste a reusable block of methods into multiple unrelated classes via <code>use</code>. <strong>Static</strong> properties/methods belong to the class itself, not an instance, and are shared across all instances. <strong>Magic methods</strong> (<code>__construct</code>, <code>__get</code>/<code>__set</code>, <code>__call</code>, <code>__toString</code>) hook into PHP's default object behavior.</p>

        <div class="subhead">Why interviewers ask it</div>
        <p>This is the baseline gate for any Laravel role — Laravel's entire architecture (contracts, service providers, facades) is built on interfaces and abstract classes, so shaky OOP fundamentals show up immediately once the interview moves into framework internals.</p>

        <div class="subhead">Real-world use case</div>
        <p>In your CampVine refactor, defining a <code>PaymentGatewayInterface</code> with a concrete <code>StripeGateway</code> and <code>ManualGateway</code> implementation is exactly this pattern — the booking logic depends only on the interface, so swapping payment providers doesn't touch business logic. Traits are the natural fit for cross-cutting behavior like an <code>HasUuid</code> or <code>Cacheable</code> trait shared across otherwise-unrelated Eloquent models.</p>

        <div class="subhead mistakes">Common mistakes</div>
        <ul>
          <li>Using a trait where the relationship is really "is-a" (should be inheritance/interface) rather than "has-behavior-of" — traits are for shared behavior, not shared identity.</li>
          <li>Confusing an abstract class (can have implementation + state, single inheritance) with an interface (contract only, a class can implement many).</li>
          <li>Making everything static "for convenience," which makes code hard to test since static calls can't be mocked/injected as easily as instance dependencies.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="subhead">Interview answer</div>
        <div class="callout">"I reach for an interface when I want to guarantee a contract across implementations I don't control the internals of — like swappable payment gateways — and an abstract class when there's real shared logic I want subclasses to inherit plus a few methods I want to force them to define themselves. Traits are for behavior that cuts across an otherwise unrelated class hierarchy, like a UUID-generation trait shared by models that have nothing else in common. I avoid static methods for anything I'll need to mock in tests — they break dependency injection."</div>

        <div class="subhead">Follow-up questions</div>
        <ul class="followups">
          <li>Can a class implement multiple interfaces but extend only one class — why is that the design?</li>
          <li>What happens if two traits used in the same class define a method with the same name?</li>
          <li>When would you choose an abstract class over an interface with default trait behavior?</li>
        </ul>

        <pre><code><span class="kw">interface</span> <span class="fn">PaymentGatewayInterface</span> {
  <span class="kw">public</span> <span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">charge</span>(<span class="kw">float</span> $amount): <span class="kw">bool</span>;
}

<span class="kw">abstract</span> <span class="kw">class</span> <span class="fn">BaseGateway</span> <span class="kw">implements</span> PaymentGatewayInterface {
  <span class="kw">protected</span> <span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">logTransaction</span>(<span class="kw">float</span> $amount): <span class="kw">void</span> { <span class="cmt">/* shared */</span> }
  <span class="kw">abstract</span> <span class="kw">public</span> <span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">charge</span>(<span class="kw">float</span> $amount): <span class="kw">bool</span>; <span class="cmt">// subclasses must implement</span>
}

<span class="kw">trait</span> <span class="fn">HasUuid</span> {
  <span class="kw">public</span> <span class="kw">static</span> <span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">bootHasUuid</span>() {
    <span class="kw">static</span>::<span class="fn">creating</span>(<span class="kw">fn</span>($model) => $model->id = <span class="fn">Str</span>::<span class="fn">uuid</span>());
  }
}

<span class="kw">class</span> <span class="fn">StripeGateway</span> <span class="kw">extends</span> BaseGateway {
  <span class="kw">public</span> <span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">charge</span>(<span class="kw">float</span> $amount): <span class="kw">bool</span> { <span class="cmt">/* Stripe-specific */</span> <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="kw">true</span>; }
}</code><button class="copy-btn">copy</button></pre>

        <div class="subhead best">Best practices</div>
        <ul>
          <li>Program against interfaces in constructors/type-hints so implementations can be swapped and mocked in tests.</li>
          <li>Keep traits small and behavior-focused; if a trait is accumulating unrelated methods, it's a sign it should be split or replaced with composition.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <!-- ============ TOPIC 2 ============ -->
      <section class="topic" data-topic="2" id="t2">
        <div class="topic-head">
          <h2><span class="tagnum">02.</span> Composer, Autoloading &amp; PSR-4 Namespaces</h2>
          <div class="topic-controls">
            <span class="diff mid">MID</span>
            <button class="star-btn" data-bm="2">☆</button>
            <button class="check-btn" data-ck="2">✓</button>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p><strong>Explanation.</strong> Composer is PHP's dependency manager — <code>composer.json</code> declares required packages and their version constraints, <code>composer.lock</code> pins the exact resolved versions for reproducible installs across environments. <strong>Autoloading</strong> means you never manually <code>require</code> class files — Composer generates an autoloader (typically <strong>PSR-4</strong>) that maps namespace prefixes to directory paths, so referencing <code>App\Services\PaymentService</code> automatically loads <code>app/Services/PaymentService.php</code> on first use. Namespaces prevent class name collisions between your code and third-party packages and organize large codebases logically, mirroring the folder structure by convention.</p>

        <div class="subhead">Why interviewers ask it</div>
        <p>It's a quick fluency check for whether you understand what's happening under Laravel's conventions rather than just following folder patterns by habit — relevant the moment you restructure a codebase or debug a "class not found" error.</p>

        <div class="subhead">Real-world use case</div>
        <p>Directly relevant to your CampVine DDD refactor — introducing bounded-context folders (e.g. <code>app/Domain/Booking</code>, <code>app/Domain/Payment</code>) instead of Laravel's flat default structure requires updating the PSR-4 mapping in <code>composer.json</code> and running <code>composer dump-autoload</code> so the new namespace paths resolve correctly.</p>

        <div class="subhead mistakes">Common mistakes</div>
        <ul>
          <li>Manually editing vendor files instead of extending them, then losing the changes on the next <code>composer update</code>.</li>
          <li>Committing <code>composer.lock</code> inconsistently — not committing it at all causes "works on my machine" version drift between environments.</li>
          <li>Not understanding that renaming/moving a class requires the namespace declaration to match its new path exactly, or the PSR-4 autoloader silently fails to find it.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="subhead">Interview answer</div>
        <div class="callout">"Composer resolves and locks dependency versions via composer.lock so every environment installs the exact same tree, and its PSR-4 autoloader maps namespace prefixes straight to folder paths, so I never manually require files — I just reference the fully-qualified class name and Composer's generated autoloader finds it. When I restructure code into domain folders for something like a DDD refactor, I add the new namespace mapping to composer.json and run composer dump-autoload to regenerate the class map."</div>

        <div class="subhead">Follow-up questions</div>
        <ul class="followups">
          <li>What's the difference between composer.json and composer.lock, and why commit both?</li>
          <li>What happens if a class's namespace doesn't match its file path under PSR-4?</li>
          <li>How would you add a custom namespace mapping for a new domain folder structure?</li>
        </ul>

        <pre><code><span class="cmt">// composer.json — PSR-4 autoload mapping</span>
{
  <span class="str">"autoload"</span>: {
    <span class="str">"psr-4"</span>: {
      <span class="str">"App\\"</span>: <span class="str">"app/"</span>,
      <span class="str">"App\\Domain\\"</span>: <span class="str">"app/Domain/"</span>
    }
  }
}

<span class="cmt">// After adding a new namespace mapping, regenerate the autoloader:</span>
<span class="cmt">// $ composer dump-autoload</span>

<span class="kw">namespace</span> App\Domain\Booking;
<span class="kw">class</span> <span class="fn">BookingService</span> { <span class="cmt">/* app/Domain/Booking/BookingService.php */</span> }</code><button class="copy-btn">copy</button></pre>

        <div class="subhead best">Best practices</div>
        <ul>
          <li>Always commit <code>composer.lock</code> for applications (not for reusable packages) to guarantee identical installs across dev/staging/prod.</li>
          <li>Never edit files in <code>vendor/</code> directly — extend, decorate, or publish a config/view override instead.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

